Travel insurance classification¶

The following project aims to build several ML classifiers which may help travel agencies to predict if their clients decide to buy an insurance during introductory offering. Project was divided into sections which covers exploratory data analysis, data preprocessing, training models and assessment of their prediction abilities.

As an outcome, four different classifiers were built: k-Nearest Neighbours, Naive Bayes Classifier, Logistic Regression and Classification Tree. Various performance measures were used to evaluate models' performances. Additionally, to handle issue with class-inbalanced data, models were assessed for two different thresholds. Another method used was SMOTE algorithm which is example of oversampling.

The results of the project shows that Classification Tree has the best classification abilities and outperforms other models. Additionally, all built classifiers are good in detecting people who are not keen to buy an insurance during introductory offering but are rather poor in detecting individuals who buy a insurance. Methods applied to boost the ability of positive classes classification have worked but resulted in drop of overall model accuracy and ability to detect negative classes. After comparison, the basic Classification Tree model was still better than other models. K-Nearest Neigbour was selected as an alternative, which can identify people who buy an insurance better than the Tree.

1.2 Variables description¶

The analysed dataset consists of 1000 records and 9 columns. First 8 features describe customers of travel agency. The last column is target variable which states if the person bought the insurance or nor. Dataset doesn't have any missing values. Detailed column descriprions are as follows:

  • Age - age of the customer,
  • Employment Type - the sector in which customer is employed,
  • Graduate Or Not - whether the customer is college graduate or not,
  • Annual Income - the yearly income of the customer in indian rupees,
  • Family Members - number of members in customer's family
  • Chronic Diseases - whether the customer suffers from any major disease or conditions like diabetes, high bp, asthama, etc.,
  • Frequent Flyer - derived data based on customer's history of booking air tickets on atleast 4 different instances in the last 2 years,
  • Ever Travelled Abroad - has the customer ever travelled to a foreign country,
  • Travel Insurance - did the customer buy travel insurance package during introductory offering held.

class color:
    """Enables formatting printed strings."""
    RED = '\033[91m'
    BOLD = '\033[1m'
    UNDERLINE = '\033[4m'
    END = '\033[0m'

def get_freq_matrix(series_1, series_2, percentage=False):
    """Returns matrix of values frequencies between two categorical columns."""
    s_1_unique = [str(s) for s in series_1.unique()]
    s_2_unique = [str(s) for s in series_2.unique()]
    
    temp_df = pd.DataFrame({"col_1": series_1.astype(str), "col_2": series_2.astype(str)})
    freq_matrix = pd.DataFrame(index=s_1_unique, columns=s_2_unique)
    n = len(series_1)
    
    for s_1 in s_1_unique:
        for s_2 in s_2_unique:
            freq_matrix.loc[s_1, s_2] = len(temp_df[(temp_df["col_1"] == s_1) & (temp_df["col_2"] == s_2)])
            if percentage:
                freq_matrix.loc[s_1, s_2] /= n
            
    return freq_matrix

    """Swap keys and values in dictionary."""

3. Data standardization¶

In this part the train and test set were standardized using the mean and standard deviation calculated from training set. Standardization can be beneficial, because improves the numerical stability of the model and often reduces time of model building. For some models, such as kNN, standarization is essential, since variables given in different units would mislead the algorithm which is based on distance metrics.

In [23]:
def scale_train_test(X_train, X_test):
    """
    Calculates mean (m) and standard deviation (sd) 
    of a training set and standardizes both train and test set 
    According to the formula z = (x - m) / sd.
    """
    m, sd = X_train.mean(), X_train.std()
    X_train_scaled = (X_train - m) / sd
    X_test_scaled = (X_test - m) / sd
    return X_train_scaled, X_test_scaled
In [24]:
X_train_scaled, X_test_scaled = scale_train_test(X_train, X_test)

4. Models training¶

This section vocers training 4 models: k-Nearest Neighbours, Naive Bayes Classifier, Logistic Regression and Classification Tree and evaluation of their performance.

k-Nearest Neighbor Classifier¶

K-Nearest Neighbor Classifier is the first model we train.

In k-Nearest Neighbor Classifier we consider $N$ pairs $(x_1, g_1), ..., (x_N, g_N)$ where $x_i$ is a feature vector of $i$-th observation in a training set and $g_i$ is class label, which takes values in $\{0, 1\}$ for binary classification problem. The given query point $x_0$ is classified to the class which is most freequent among $k$ closest points in its neighborhood. Closest neighbors are usually defined by Euclidean distance after standardization of quantitative features in dataset, to have a mean 0 and variance 1, as they are usually in different units. For the best choices of tuning parameter $k$, the plot showing accuracy scores as a function of neighborhood size was drawn.

In [25]:
skf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=seed)
skf_acc, acc_train, auc_train = [], [], []

k_list = list(range(1,30,2))
for k in k_list:
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    knn.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
    y_pred_train = knn.predict(X_train_scaled)
    acc_train.append(accuracy_score(y_pred_train, y_train))
    auc_train.append(roc_auc_score(y_pred_train, y_train))
    skf_acc_k = []
    for train_idx, test_idx in skf.split(X_train_scaled, y_train):
        X_train_fold, X_test_fold = X_train_scaled.iloc[train_idx], X_train_scaled.iloc[test_idx]
        y_train_fold, y_test_fold = y_train.iloc[train_idx], y_train.iloc[test_idx]
        knn.fit(X_train_fold, y_train_fold)
        y_pred = knn.predict(X_test_fold)
        skf_acc_k.append(accuracy_score(y_pred, y_test_fold))
    skf_acc.append(mean(skf_acc_k))

k_tune_df = pd.DataFrame({"Number of Neighbors": k_list,"Train Accuracy": acc_train, "Train ROC AUC": auc_train, "Stratified 5-fold CV": skf_acc})

Even though the train accuracy increases as parameter $k$ increases, the cross-validation accuracy tends to go in opposite direction. It is a sign that model becomes overfitted as number of neigbours grows. According to the plot and keeping in mind that $k$ should be odd number, enough low to poses ability of generalization but not too low to not undefit the data, it was decided to take $k$ equal to $5$ for training final model. The k parameter value is selected with vettical line on the plot.

def fevaluate_model(y_test, y_pred):
    """
    Returns dictionary of main metrics used to evaluate a classification model,
    Comaprind predictions with actual values.
    Takes two arguments: real Y values and predicted Y values respectively.
    """
    # acc, roc_auc
    acc = accuracy_score(y_pred, y_test)
    err = 1 - acc
    auc = roc_auc_score(y_pred, y_test)

    # calculate TN, FN, FP, TP
    TN, FN, FP, TP = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred).ravel()
    # calculate specificity, sensitivity, positive predictive value, and negative predictive value 
    recall  = TP / (TP+FN)
    specificity  = TN / (TN+FP)
    PPV = TP / (TP+FP) # precision
    NPV = TN / (TN+FN)
    
    # F1 score
    F1 = 2*(recall*PPV)/(recall+PPV)
    
    perf_metrics = {
        "Accuracy": acc,
        "Error rate": err,
        "AUC": auc,
        "Recall": recall,
        "Specificity": specificity,
        "PPV": PPV,
        "NPV": NPV,
        "F1": F1,
    }
    
    return perf_metrics
        

def evaluate_model(clf, X_test, y_test, X_train=None, y_train=None, verbose=True, threshold=0.5):
    """
    Returns dictionary of metrics assessing model performance on test set and,
    Optionally, on train set for a given classification threshold. 
    Takes three mandatory arguments: trained model, X test set and y test vector.
    Optional arguments are: X train set, y train vector, boolean parameter indicating,
    If results should be printed (default True), and threshold value (default 0.5).
    """
    def eval_print(metrics_dict, set_name="test"):
        """Prints values of model performance metrcics stored in dictionary."""
        print(color.BOLD + f"Evaluation measures on {set_name} set:" + color.END)
        for key, value in metrics_dict.items():
            print(f"{key}: {round(value, 3)}")
        print("-"*40)
    
    perf_metrics = {}
    
    if X_train is not None and y_train is not None:
        # check model performance on train set
        y_pred_train = (clf.predict_proba(X_train)[:,1] >= threshold).astype(bool)
        train_metrics = fevaluate_model(y_pred_train, y_train)
        
        if verbose:
            eval_print(train_metrics, set_name="train")
        
        perf_metrics["Train"] = train_metrics
        
    # check model performance on test set
    y_pred_test = (clf.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1] >= threshold).astype(bool)
    test_metrics = fevaluate_model(y_pred_test, y_test)
        
    if verbose:
        eval_print(test_metrics)
        
    perf_metrics["Test"] = test_metrics
        
    return perf_metrics

Train and test performance metrics of kNN are very similar, so only test set results are going to be described.

The built k-NN classifier is able to predict 84.5% of test observations correctly. Area under the ROC is 78.6% what gives way better result than random classifier but its value as well as level of model accuracy are not exceptionally good. Value of recall, which express proportion of observations from positive class which were predicted correctly, is equal to 62.9% only. Specificity indicates that 94.2% of people who wouldn't take the insurence were correctly classified by the model. The precision (PPV) value of 0.83 says that when model predicts that person will buy an insurance, it is correct in 83% of the time. The F1 score which measures both precision and recall equals 71,6%. In general, these results are not very high and would not be helpful for travel agency as model ability of identification people taking the insurance is rather poor. It addresses that one should take steps to improve the model performance or try to build different model.

def plot_conf_matrix_clf(clf, X_test, y_test):
    """
    Plots confusion matrix based on trained model, 
    X test set, and y test, provided as arguments.
    """
    color = 'black'
    matrix = plot_confusion_matrix(clf, X_test, y_test, cmap=plt.cm.Blues)
    matrix.ax_.set_title('Confusion Matrix', color=color)
    plt.xlabel('Predicted Label', color=color)
    plt.ylabel('True Label', color=color)
    plt.gcf().axes[0].tick_params(colors=color)
    plt.gcf().axes[1].tick_params(colors=color)
    plt.grid(False)
    plt.show()
    
def plot_conf_matrix(y_test, y_pred):
    """
    Plots confusion matrix based on predicted
    And real values of target variable y.
    """
    color = 'black'
    cf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    ax = sns.heatmap(cf_matrix, annot=True, cmap=plt.cm.Blues, fmt='g')
    ax.set_xlabel('Predicted labels', color=color)
    ax.set_ylabel('True labels', color=color)
    ax.set_title('Confusion Matrix', color=color)
    plt.grid(False)
    plt.show()

def plot_decision_boundary(data, x_axis_col, y_axis_col, y_pred_col, y_true_col):

Naive Bayesian Classifier¶

Naive Bayesian Classifier was second model built in this project.

Having the observation $X = (x_1, ..., x_p)$ and $m$ classes $C_1, ..., C_m$, the Naive Bayes Classifier predicts that $X$ belongs to the class having the highest probability, conditioned on $X$, given as $P(C_i|X)$. By Bayes’ theorem, it can be transformed as follows:

$$ P(C_i|X) = \frac{P(X|C_i) \cdot P(C_i)}{P(X)} $$

Because the equation above can be computationally expensive, Naive Bayes' technique makes a naive assumption that the classes are equally likely, so $P(C_i)=...=P(C_m)$, and that the attributes' values are conditionally independent of one another. Thus,

$$ P(X|C_i) = P(x_1|C_i) \cdot\ ...\ \cdot P(x_p|C_i) $$

As $P(x_1|C_i), ..., P(x_p|C_i)$ can be easily estimated from the training set, the query point $X$ is classified to the class which maximizes this component.

If attribute $A_k$ is categorical, $P(x_k|C_i)$ is calculated as number of training examples having value $x_k$ of $A_k$ and belonging to the $C_i$ class divided by number of points in class $C_i$. If the attribute is continuous, it is assumed to follow the normal distribution. Next, the mean $\mu_{C_i}$ and standard deviation $\sigma_{C_i}$ of $A_k$ from examples belonging to $C_i$ are calculated, and probability $P(x_k|C_i)$ is given as $g(x_k, \mu_{C_i}, \sigma_{C_i})$, where $g$ is probability density function of a normal distribution.

Because some features included in this dataset are categorical while other continuous, Mixed Naive Bayes model was built for this task.

To predict insurance purchase, the Mixed Bayes Classifier was built. Person age, annual income and faimly members were taken as numeric variables. The remaining features were assumed to be categorical. The model accuracy is 0.82. It means that model is able to predict 82% of people decisions about buying insurance. The precision value of 0.771 says that when model predicts that person would buy an insurance, it is correct in 77.1% of the time. Additionally, recall equal to 0.597 means that model correctly identifies only 59,7% of all indivisuals who bought an insurance. Specificity indicates that 92% of people who did not buy an insurance were correctly identified by the model. The F1 score equals 67.3%. Those results suggests that Naive Bayes Classifier performance is quite poor, especially predicting observations from positive class.

Logistic Regression¶

Logistic regression model represents logarithm of odds (ratio of condidtional probabilities that $X$ belongs to the first and second class) via linear function in $X = (x_1, ..., x_p)$, while at the same time probabilities remain in $[0, 1]$. It has the following form:

$$ \log{\frac{P(C_1|X)}{1 - P(C_1|X)}} = \beta_{0} + \beta_1X $$

After some calculations, it can be transformed to the form of sigmoid function:

$$ P(C_1|X) = \frac{1}{1 + e^{-(\beta_{0} + \beta_1X)}} $$

Having given the training set, model parameters are estimated with use of Maximum Likelihood Method.

Logistic regression model was trained on the standardized train set data and its accuracy, equal to 84.0%, is similar to k-NN model. The precision score is equal to 84.1%, recall equals 59.7% and specificity equals 94.9%. It means that 84.1% of people thought by the classifier to buy insurance, actually did it. Value of recall says that out off all people who bought insurance, only 59.7% were correctly forecasted. Specificity indicates that 94.9% of people travelling without insurance were classified to the correct class. The F1 score which measures the overall performance, including both the precision and recall, equals 69.8%.

Classification Tree¶

As per classification tree model, it predicts that query observation $X$ belongs to the most commonly occurring class among training observations in the region to which it belongs. To build the regions, the recursive binary splitting technique is used. The approach recursively splits the preditor space, what is indicated by adding new branches from top to dow of the tree, aiming to make a high quality split. The evaluation of split qulity is done based on Gini index (G):

$$ G = \sum^{K}_{k=1}{\hat{p}_{mk}(1 - \hat{p}_{mk})} $$

or alternatively, based on Entropy (D), given as:

$$ D = - \sum^{K}_{k=1}{\hat{p}_{mk}\log{\hat{p}_{mk}}} $$

The $\hat{p}_{mk}$ represents proportion of observation from $k$-th class being in $m$-th region. Both metrics take on a small value if the $m$-th node is pure, what means that after the split, one class predominate over the rest.

The built classification tree model seems to be overfitted - assessment metrics calculated on the train set are much better than these estimated for train set. To handle this issue, it was decided to apply hyperparameter tunning to reduce model variance and find tree which has enough ability to generalize the patterns and make good predictions on test set.

Hyperparameter tunning¶

In [40]:
max_depth = list(range(2,10,1))
min_samples_split = list(range(5,16,5))

skf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=seed)
skf_acc, skf_auc, depth_list, min_ss_list = [], [], [], []

for s in min_samples_split:
    for d in max_depth:
        clf_tree = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=d, min_samples_split=s, random_state=seed)
        clf_tree.fit(X_train, y_train)
        y_pred_train = clf_tree.predict(X_train)
        skf_acc_s, skf_auc_s = [], []
        for train_idx, test_idx in skf.split(X_train, y_train):
            X_train_fold, X_test_fold = X_train.iloc[train_idx], X_train.iloc[test_idx]
            y_train_fold, y_test_fold = y_train.iloc[train_idx], y_train.iloc[test_idx]
            clf_tree.fit(X_train_fold, y_train_fold)
            y_pred = clf_tree.predict(X_test_fold)
            skf_acc_s.append(accuracy_score(y_pred, y_test_fold))
            skf_auc_s.append(roc_auc_score(y_pred, y_test_fold))
        skf_acc.append(mean(skf_acc_s))
        skf_auc.append(mean(skf_auc_s))
        min_ss_list.append(s)
        depth_list.append(d)
    
tree_tune_df = pd.DataFrame({"Tree size": depth_list,
                             "Min. samples split": min_ss_list, 
                             "Cross-Validation ROC AUC": skf_auc, 
                             "Cross-Validation Accuracy": skf_acc})

The plots below show the cross-validation accuracy and cross-validation ROC AUC value for different tree levels and minimum samples to split. One can easily notice that based on accuracy, the best number of tree levels is 3. For most cases, accuracy score dicreases as tree size increases. According to the second plot, ROC AUC has the best value for tree size equal to 2. For small tree sizes, total minimum samples to split the node seem to not differ between tested values. For larger trees, minimum value equal to 10 seems to sligtly outperform other parameter values. It is probably because higher value of this parameter reduces effect of overfitting caused by building too large tree.

To build the final model, it was decided to take maximum depth equal to 3 and minimum number of samples in the node to make a split equal to 10.

# data frame storing classification results of all the models
master_results = pd.DataFrame(columns=["Model", "Class imbalance approache", "Accuracy", "Recall", "Specificity", "Precision", "AUC"])

def update_master_results(model_names, model_version, models_pm, master_results):
    """Updates master_results data frame with performance metrics of new models."""
    
    for i, model_name in enumerate(model_names):
        test_pm = models_pm[i].get("Test")
        acc = test_pm.get("Accuracy")
        recall = test_pm.get("Recall")
        specificity = test_pm.get("Specificity")
        ppv = test_pm.get("PPV")
        auc = test_pm.get("AUC")
        new_row = [model_name, model_version, acc, recall, specificity, ppv, auc]
        master_results.loc[len(master_results)] = new_row
    
    return master_results

5. Improving Classification of Class-Imbalanced Data¶

All the models trained and presented in the above section have tendency to obtain good results in predicting observations from negative class and poor results when predicting point belonging to the positive class. It is not good, as travel agency is probably more intrested in recognition of people who may potentially buy the insurance. The reason of that is class imbalance problem which is present in this dataset. In short, it means that predicted class labels occure in different proportion. Because traditional algorithms aims to minimize the overall number of errors and treat false positive and false negative errors equally, they might not be suitable to predict class-imbalanced data. To imrpve the model performance in such case, one can apply several methods, including:

  • moving the classification threshold
  • oversampling and undersampling
  • ensemble methods

To address this problem in the following project, two techniques were applied and tested: threshold moving and SMOTE algorithm being example of oversampling method.

Threshold moving¶

Multiple threshold values were tested before selecting the final one. It was decided to change the threshold to 35% as for this value, model evaluation metrics seemd to be the best.

In [51]:

After setting threshold value to 35%, models ability to recognize positive cases increased. The biggest difference was noticed for k-NN model, for which recall increased by about 17%. On the other hand, recall hasn't changed at all for classification tree, which results are relatively good anyway. All models except the tree lost accuracy and specificity scores in favour of recall score. Despite that, the increase of recall was not very high comparing to accuracy and specificity drop. Taking it into consideration, it is hard to say that models are better after changing the threshold, even if they are able to recognize people who bought an insurance with higher accuracy.

SMOTE Oversampling for Imbalanced Dataset¶

SMOTE algorithm is oversampling technique which, instead of simple dupicating observations from minority class, generates new points which are combination of current observations and their nearest neigbours. One iteration is done by choosing random point from the minority class. Then, its k nearest neigbours are found based on selected distance metrics and random neigbour is selected. Features of newly added point are made of values calculated as middle value between values of variables of current point and its random nearest neigbour.

6. Conclusion¶

The aim of the following project was to build and compare multiple machine learning models which are meant to forecast if the traveller buy the insurance from travel agency based on their personal data. To do so, four model were estimated in three different version as attempt to handle class imbalance problem. First model, k-Nearest Neighbour, was trained on scaled data. The model obtained the test accuracy equal to 84.5%, precision of 83% and recall equal to 62.9%. Those metrices changed a little after adjusting the classification threshold and applying SMOTE oversampling. In general, model accuracy and specificity decreased which was the cost of obtaining higher recall. The second model was Naive Bayes Classifier which has the worst accuracy in basic version, but the model hasn't improved significantly also after moving the threshold and using the SMOTE. Third and fourth models were Logistic Regression and Classification Tree respectively. While Logistic Regression perfromance was rather average and did not outperform k-NN and Naive Bayes, the Tree model evaluation metrics was relatively good. Despite not very high ability to detect insurance purchases, it has high accuracy equal to 87.5% and very high specificity and precision. At the same time tree has the highest recall among the all basic models anyway.

Looking at the metrics and spider plots below one can notice that applying methods which are meant to handle class imbalance problem, the model recall usually increases. However, it is usually done at the cost of drop in accuracy and other metrices such as specificity and precision.

After analysing the results below, it seems that the best model is Classification Tree without applying any approaches improving classification for class imbalanced data. Alternativel, travel agency could choose k-Nearest Neighbor Classifier with threshold set to 35% if it is more interested in better ability to detect positive samples than overall accuracy.

Obviously, the accuracy and other metrices of both models are too low to trust classification decisions without any doubt of Tree as well as k-NN model. But at the same time, the models can be still important tools which may help travel agency in making better business decisions. Undoubtedly, decision driven by suggestions from the models, and analysed carrefully by analysts and managers, are less risky than those driven only by intuition and basic data analysis.

In [61]:
def spider_plot(metrics_lists, labels, plot_title):
    categories = ['Accuracy', 'Recall', 'Specificity', 'Precision', 'AUC']
    N = len(categories)
    angles = [n / float(N) * 2 * np.pi for n in range(N)]
    angles += angles[:1]

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
    ax = plt.subplot(111, polar=True)
    ax.set_theta_offset(np.pi / 2)
    ax.set_theta_direction(-1)
    plt.xticks(angles[:-1], categories, size=15)
    ax.set_rlabel_position(0.3)
    plt.yticks([0.5, 0.6, 0.7, 0.8, 0.9], color="grey", size=12)
    plt.ylim(0, 1)
    
    for i in range(len(metrics_lists)):
        values = metrics_lists[i]
        values += values[:1]
        ax.plot(angles, values, linewidth=1.1, linestyle='solid', label=labels[i], color=colors[i])
        
    plt.title(plot_title, size=20, y=1.05)
    plt.legend(prop={'size': 15})
    plt.show()
